    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the dice thing makes sense, but it still feels a bit weird. like, how can they \"know\" what the other is doing without anything traveling between them? i remember reading something about \"spooky action at a distance\" - why did einstein call it that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called quantum entanglement \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to violate his belief in locality, which states that objects are only directly affected by their immediate surroundings. He couldn't fathom how two particles could instantly affect each other without any visible means of communication. It's like if your friend telepathically knew what you were thinking and could change their mind accordingly, even if they were on the other side of the world. Einstein was troubled by this idea because it contradicted his theory of relativity, which says that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light.\n\nIn the world of quantum mechanics, however, entanglement doesn't involve any faster-than-light communication. It's more like a shared secret between the particles, where their states are intertwined in a way that doesn't require any physical connection or signal. It's as if they are dancing together in perfect harmony, regardless of the distance between them. This \"spooky\" behavior is a fundamental aspect of the quantum world, and it continues to baffle and fascinate scientists even today.",
      "source": "target",
